What if your data doesn't look linear at all? let's look at some more realistic-looking page speed / purchase data:

msg.data:
Polynomial Regression

What if your data doesn’t look linear at all? let’s look at some more realistic-looking page speed / purchase data:

paragraphs.text:
%python

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

np.random.seed(2)
pageSpeeds = np.random.normal(3.0, 1.0, 1000)
purchaseAmount = np.random.normal(50.0, 10.0, 1000) / pageSpeeds

plt.scatter(pageSpeeds, purchaseAmount)

%md
numpy has a handy polyfit function we can use, to let us construct an nth-degree polynomial model of our data that minimizes sqared error. Let's try it with a 4th degree polynomial

msg.data: numpy has a handy polyfit function we can use, to let us construct an nth-degree polynomial model of our data that minimizes sqared error. Let’s try it with a 4th degree polynomial

paragraphs.text:
%python
x = np.array(pageSpeeds)
y = np.array(purchaseAmount)
#compute a 4th grade polynomial
p4 = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(x, y, 4))

%md
We'll visualize our original scatter plot, together with a plot of our predicted values using the polynomial for page speed times ranging from 0-7 seconds:

msg.data: We’ll visualize our original scatter plot, together with a plot of our predicted values using the polynomial for page speed times ranging from 0-7 seconds:

paragraphs.text:
%python

xp = np.linspace(0, 7, 100)
plt.scatter(x, y)
plt.plot(xp, p4(xp), c='r')
plt.show()

%md
Looks pretty good! Let's measure the r-sqaured error:

msg.data: Looks pretty good! Let’s measure the r-sqaured error:

paragraphs.text:
%python
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

r2 = r2_score(y, p4(x))
print r2
